TY  - JOUR
T1  - On the Neutrality of Money
AU  - Saving, Thomas R.
Y1  - 1973/01/01
PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260008
DO  - 10.1086/260008
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 98
EP  - 119
VL  - 81
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The neutrality of changes in the monetary base and reserve requirements is examined assuming the existence of two forms of money and an arbitrary number of other financial assets. Necessary and sufficient conditions for a policy to be neutral are developed. Several forms of institutional structure for the banking system are examined to see whether these structures satisfy the derived necessary conditions. It is shown that reserve requirement changes are neutral under very restrictive conditions. Moreover, even the neutrality of monetary base changes requires that money maintenance cost functions be homogeneous of degree zero in nominal money and prices.
AB  - The neutrality of changes in the monetary base and reserve requirements is examined assuming the existence of two forms of money and an arbitrary number of other financial assets. Necessary and sufficient conditions for a policy to be neutral are developed. Several forms of institutional structure for the banking system are examined to see whether these structures satisfy the derived necessary conditions. It is shown that reserve requirement changes are neutral under very restrictive conditions. Moreover, even the neutrality of monetary base changes requires that money maintenance cost functions be homogeneous of degree zero in nominal money and prices.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260008
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260008
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Aid, Foreign Private Investment, Savings, and Growth in Less Developed Countries
AU  - Papanek, Gustav F.
Y1  - 1973/01/01
PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260009
DO  - 10.1086/260009
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 120
EP  - 130
VL  - 81
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Cross-country regression analysis is applied to thirty-four countries for the 1950s and fifty-one countries for the 1960s. When foreign aid, foreign investment, other inflows and domestic savings are treated as separate independent variables: (a) savings and foreign inflows explain over a third of growth; (b) foreign aid has a substantially greater effect than the other variables; (c) correlation between aid and foreign private investment is not significant; (d) only for Asia do the four variables explain much; and (e) growth is not correlated with exports, education, per capita income, or country size. Savings are highly correlated with exports and per capita income, not with country size.
AB  - Cross-country regression analysis is applied to thirty-four countries for the 1950s and fifty-one countries for the 1960s. When foreign aid, foreign investment, other inflows and domestic savings are treated as separate independent variables: (a) savings and foreign inflows explain over a third of growth; (b) foreign aid has a substantially greater effect than the other variables; (c) correlation between aid and foreign private investment is not significant; (d) only for Asia do the four variables explain much; and (e) growth is not correlated with exports, education, per capita income, or country size. Savings are highly correlated with exports and per capita income, not with country size.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260009
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260009
Y2  - 2024/03/22
