TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Cross-sectional Analysis of Women's Participation in the Professions
AU  - Blitz, Rudolph C.
AU  - Ow, Chin Hock
Y1  - 1973/01/01
PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260010
DO  - 10.1086/260010
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 131
EP  - 144
VL  - 81
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The professions constitute an intellectual elite. Hence, it is of interest how women fare in this elite. This study attempts to explain differences among states of the proportion of women in the professions based on the 1960 census. This is done with demand and supply equations using the following variables: state per capita income, industrial structure, female educational endowment, availability of domestics, and ratio of male to female professional income. All of the variables performed well except the income variable. The poor performance of the latter seems to be due to its aggregative character and necessary statistical manipulations.
AB  - The professions constitute an intellectual elite. Hence, it is of interest how women fare in this elite. This study attempts to explain differences among states of the proportion of women in the professions based on the 1960 census. This is done with demand and supply equations using the following variables: state per capita income, industrial structure, female educational endowment, availability of domestics, and ratio of male to female professional income. All of the variables performed well except the income variable. The poor performance of the latter seems to be due to its aggregative character and necessary statistical manipulations.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260010
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260010
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Putty-Clay Capital and Small-Sample Properties of Neoclassical Estimators
AU  - Gapinski, James H.
Y1  - 1973/01/01
PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260011
DO  - 10.1086/260011
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 145
EP  - 157
VL  - 81
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In this paper it is assumed that capital is putty-clay, that technical progress is embodied, and that the ex ante production function is CES in form. In this setting the Monte Carlo technique is used to examine the small-sample properties of several neoclassical estimators of the ex ante capital intensity parameter and of the ex ante elasticity of substitution. Central to the analysis a putty-clay model in which the production process is stochastic. This model suggests a regression specification which is consistent with the assumed nature of capital, and the properties of its estimators are examined.
AB  - In this paper it is assumed that capital is putty-clay, that technical progress is embodied, and that the ex ante production function is CES in form. In this setting the Monte Carlo technique is used to examine the small-sample properties of several neoclassical estimators of the ex ante capital intensity parameter and of the ex ante elasticity of substitution. Central to the analysis a putty-clay model in which the production process is stochastic. This model suggests a regression specification which is consistent with the assumed nature of capital, and the properties of its estimators are examined.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260011
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260011
Y2  - 2024/03/22
